label.value: circadian rhythm sleep disorder, irregular sleep wake type

value.value: A circadian sleep disorder characterized by at least three sleep episodes per 24-hour period, irregularly from day to day.

label.value: circadian rhythm sleep disorder, jet lag type

value.value: A circadian sleep disorder that results from traveling across time zones.

label.value: circadian rhythm sleep disorder, shift work type

value.value: A circadian sleep disorder that occurs when work schedules force people to be awake when their circadian rhythms dictate that they should be sleeping. It is classified as a Circadian Rhythm Disorder (CRD) and is extrinsic, i.e. caused by external behavioral factors.

label.value: large cell lung carcinoma, clear cell variant

value.value: A morphologic variant of large cell lung carcinoma characterized by a predominance of clear cells that may or may not contain glycogen.
A sex cord-stromal tumor arising from the ovary, without metastatic potential.
Infections with bacteria of the genus clostridium.
A disease caused by infection with Bifidobacterium.
A disease caused by infection with Peptostreptococcus.
A disease caused by infection with Neorickettsia.

Cognitive disorders characterized by an impaired ability to perceive the nature of objects or concepts through use of the sense organs. These include spatial neglect syndromes, where an individual does not attend to visual, auditory, or sensory stimuli presented from one side of the body.

definition.value: Editor note: not in ORDO as of Apr 29 2018; Reason of obsoletion: out of scope - MONDO:excludeHistoricalDisease. Term to consider: -

value.value: Inflammation at the site of insertion of ligaments, tendons, and other fibrous structures into bone.

Acquired or developmental cognitive disorders of AUDITORY PERCEPTION characterized by a reduced ability to perceive information contained in auditory stimuli despite intact auditory pathways. Affected individuals have difficulty with speech perception, sound localization, and comprehending the meaning of inflections of speech.

A disorienting neuropsychological condition that affects perception. People experience size distortion such as micropsia, macropsia, pelopsia, or teleopsia. Size distortion may occur of other sensory modalities.
A neurological disorder in which a sensory stimulus, usually tactile but more rarely other sensory modalities, is misperceived in a location distant from the original stimulus.
A disease that involves the nerve plexus.
A disease that involves the sacral nerve plexus.
Any autosomal dominant Robinow syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the WNT5A gene.
An iridogoniodysgenesis that results from alterations in the forkhead transcription factor gene (FOXC1)
A disease that involves the visual system.

A benign diffuse vascular proliferation usually occurring in young adults. It is characterized by the formation of capillary-sized and cavernous vascular spaces. Patients present with diffuse persistent swelling.
A susceptibility or predisposition to cutaneous melanoma (disease) that is caused by an inherited modification of the individual's genome.
Any combined pituitary hormone deficiencies, genetic form in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the POU1F1 gene.
A disease that involves the apocrine sweat gland.
A disease that involves the adenohypophysis.
A benign, intermediate, or malignant cartilaginous matrix-producing neoplasm. Representative examples include osteochondroma, chondroblastoma, and chondrosarcoma.
A non-metastasizing cartilaginous matrix-producing neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic chondrocytes. Representative examples include osteochondroma and chondroma.
An infectious disease of the Mediterranean area, the Crimea, Africa, and India, caused by infection with rickettsia conorii subsp. coronorii.
An infectious disease of the Astrakhan region, Chad, Kosovo, caused by infection with rickettsia conorii subsp. caspia.

A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the squamous, glandular, or transitional cell epithelium without evidence of invasion. According to the degree of nuclear atypia, number of mitotic figures, and presence of architectural distortion, it is classified as low grade (mild dysplasia) or high grade (moderate or severe dysplasia).
A epithelial neoplasm that involves the rectum.

label.value: liver and intrahepatic bile duct neoplasm

value.value: A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the liver parenchyma or intrahepatic bile ducts. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include hepatocellular adenoma, and bile duct adenoma. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include hepatocellular carcinoma, intrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma, and lymphoma.
A epithelial neoplasm that involves the colon.

value.value: A disease that involves the cutaneous appendage.
A hamartoma characterized by localized eccrine sweat gland malformation.
Hyperplasia of the transitional epithelium of the urinary tract. Morphologically it is subdivided into flat and papillary hyperplasia. -- 2003
